from a lost placename, in which <i>banc</i> may mean ‘steep crag’. The second part of the name, <i>-banc</i>, survives in   Maybank  , but medieval forms in <i>-ban(e)</i>, <i>-bon(e)</i>, or <i>-bun</i> are also common and are sometimes later re-interpreted as <i>-born</i> and <i>-bourne</i>, leading to confusion with   Melbourne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mabon","meanings":["Scottish: from a Brittonic personal name <i>Mabon</i> or <i>Maban</i>, apparently derivatives of <i>Maponos</i>, the name of an ancient Celtic god.","Possibly also English (of Norman origin): variant of   Malbon   with loss of <i>-l-</i>.","In some cases possibly also Breton: ultimately of the same origin as the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Maybank","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Malbon  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alberède d'Albon was born in 0985, in Normandy, France as the daughter of Simon DE NEAUPHLE. She married Guillaume de Gometz in 1012, in Yvelines, Île-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1040, in La Ferté-sous-Jouarre, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 56, and was buried in Normandy, France."},"et":{"985–Abt 1040":"0985–umbes 1040","0985–1040":"0985–1040","0988–1040":"0988–1040","1004–1074":"1004–1074","0955–1015":"0955–1015","0985":"0985","Abt 1040":"umbes 1040","1004":"1004","1015":"1015","985":"0985","1012":"1012","1074":"1074","1040":"1040","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Gometz, Yvelines, Ile-De-France, France":"Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","La Ferté-sous-Jouarre, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"La Ferté-sous-Jouarre, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Montlhery, Esonne, Ile-De-France, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Neauphle-le-Château, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Neauphle-le-Château, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"985–Abt 1040":"0985–noin 1040","0985–1040":"0985–1040","0988–1040":"0988–1040","10